	<h2>About me</h2>
    <h3>&nbsp;</h3>	
	<p>In september 2008, I got the Bachelor's degree in Electronics and Communications Engineering  and  in may 2012, I got a Master's degree in Sciences and Information Technologies, both from the <a href="http://www.iztapalapa.uam.mx/" target="_blank">Universidad Autónoma Metropolitana - Iztapalapa</a> (UAM-Iztapalapa) in Mexico City.<br/><br/>

From october 2011 to date,  I am part of the <a href="http://www.electrica.cbiuami.org/" target="_blank">Department of Electrical Engineering</a> of UAM-Iztapalapa as engineering assistant.<br/><br/>

Since january 2013, I am PhD student in Information Technologies program at UAM-Iztapalapa in Mexico City. My thesis advisor is  <a href="http://victor.ramos.free.fr/index.html" target="_blank">Dr. Víctor Manuel Ramos Ramos</a>. The approach of this thesis investigation is the design of algorithms for medium access control for the IEEE 802.11 standard in the presence of heterogenous traﬃc and network interfaces.<br/><br/><br />
	  
	<h2>Wireless Networking Systems Research Group</h2>
    <h3>&nbsp;</h3>	

	<table id="contenido">
		<tr><td width="1%"></td>
			<td width="30%">
				<img src="images/wsrg-logo.png" width="180px" />
			</td>
			<td></td>
			<td width="60%">
			Led by <b>Dr. Victor Ramos</b>, the Wireless Networking Systems (WiNetSys) is a graduate research group intended to develop, implement, and analyze the performance of medium access mechanisms for a wide span of wireless systems based on the IEEE 802.11, such as heterogeneous radio access technologies, vehicular and mesh networks, as well as Radio Frequency 
			IDentification systems (RFID) under the EPCglobal specifications.
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>
